      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Interior Paint Colours When Selling a Brisbane Home
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Paint is the single highest-return pre-sale investment when it is done right, and a waste of money when it is done wrong. Here is how to choose colours that lift offers rather than limit them.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>A careful interior repaint is one of the most reliable ways to lift a sale price in Brisbane's inner east. Comparable homes with fresh, well-chosen interior paint consistently achieve five to ten per cent above homes with dated or tired interiors, on campaigns of otherwise similar quality. On a $1.4 million Morningside home, that spread is $70,000 to $140,000. A full interior repaint in a 180 square metre home typically costs between $8,000 and $14,000. The mathematics is uncontroversial. What sellers get wrong is the colour, not the spend.</p>

      <p>Interior paint goes wrong in predictable ways. Colours chosen from a small sample chip with no test on the actual wall in the actual light. Bold feature walls applied in rooms that should read calm. Warm cream on walls that the rest of the home has been updated to read cool. A twelve-month-old feature wall the vendor loves but that a buyer cannot look past. These decisions do not just fail to add value. They actively remove it.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The goal is neutrality, not beige</h2>
      <p>The single most important principle is that interior paint for sale is not about expressing taste. It is about removing friction. Every colour, tone, and finish choice should help the widest possible pool of buyers imagine themselves living in the home. A buyer walking in should not register the walls at all. They should register the space, the light, and the flow. The paint's job is to disappear.</p>

      <p>This does not mean beige. Beige has its own era, and in 2027 it dates a home as clearly as burnt orange once did. Modern neutrals are lighter, cooler, and slightly more complex than traditional beige or magnolia. The right contemporary neutral lifts the light in the room, photographs cleanly, and reads as current without feeling cold or clinical.</p>

      <p>The most reliably performing colour family in Brisbane right now is a soft warm white with a trace of grey or the slightest hint of yellow. Not stark white, which reads as builder-grade and clinical. Not grey-white, which can photograph blue in cool light. A warm white that leans just off pure white, with a low chroma undertone that keeps the whole home feeling considered.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Specific colours that consistently work</h2>
      <p>The colours below are drawn from Dulux and Haymes ranges, both of which are well stocked through Brisbane trade paint stores and widely used by Queensland painters. They are not the only colours that work, but they are a dependable starting point for a vendor who wants neutral risk.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Dulux Natural White.</strong> A soft warm white with a barely-there yellow undertone. Works in almost every Brisbane light condition, photographs cleanly, and reads as fresh without tipping into yellow. Probably the most widely specified interior colour for sale preparation in the inner east, and for good reason.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Dulux Vivid White.</strong> A cleaner, cooler white than Natural White. Use in homes with existing cool-toned finishes, grey floorboards, or stone benchtops with cool undertones. Too cool for most Queenslanders, which tend to read warm throughout.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Dulux Antique White USA.</strong> A warmer white than Natural White with a subtle yellow-cream undertone. Works well in traditional Queenslander interiors with timber floors, timber joinery, and warm colour palettes. Can read slightly creamy in cool northern light, so test carefully.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Dulux Lexicon Quarter.</strong> A cool soft white, cleaner than Natural White, without the clinical edge of pure white. Good for contemporary interiors with white kitchens, pale flooring, and modern fittings. Popular with stylists for a reason.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Haymes Pure White.</strong> A warm white sometimes specified as an alternative to Natural White. Slightly creamier in feel, and a good choice if the home has warm timber floors and existing warm fixtures.</p>

      <p>The practical decision is usually between Natural White and Lexicon Quarter. Natural White for traditional homes, homes with timber floors, and homes that already feel warm. Lexicon Quarter for contemporary homes, homes with cool flooring, and homes that have been renovated with modern stone and tile.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Always test in the actual room</h2>
      <p>Paint swatches on a fan deck look nothing like paint on a wall. Light from different orientations reads colours differently, and the existing flooring, furniture, and fittings all shift how the colour appears in place. Before committing to a whole-home repaint, buy sample pots of the two or three candidate colours and paint large A3 sample boards. Place them on walls in every orientation and in every key room, and look at them at three different times of day. The colour that holds up in every room at every time is the colour to commit to.</p>

      <p>A common mistake is choosing a colour based on how it looks in the living area alone, then discovering it reads yellow in the bedrooms and green in the bathroom. Colours behave differently in different rooms because of light direction, reflected colour from floors and fittings, and the size of the wall planes. Testing everywhere matters.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Trim, doors, and ceilings</h2>
      <p>Trim, architraves, skirtings, and doors should normally be painted in a cleaner white than the walls. A common approach is walls in Natural White or Lexicon Quarter, and trim in Dulux Vivid White in a semi-gloss or satin finish. The slight contrast makes the joinery pop, defines the architecture of the room, and reads as considered and modern.</p>

      <p>Ceilings should be painted in a flat ceiling white, one shade cleaner than the walls. A ceiling painted in the same colour as the walls can feel heavy and low. A ceiling in a clean white opens the room up and lifts the light. Use a dedicated ceiling paint rather than standard wall paint for a flatter, more uniform finish that hides minor imperfections.</p>

      <p>Internal doors are often overlooked. Dated doors painted in yellowed gloss enamel are one of the visual tells of an older interior. Repainting internal doors in a modern water-based enamel in Dulux Vivid White transforms the feel of every hallway and entry, and is almost always worth the additional couple of days of painter time.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Feature walls and bold colours</h2>
      <p>Feature walls almost never help a sale. The vendor's favourite accent wall in deep navy, forest green, or terracotta is almost always a negative to a buyer who walks in and immediately starts planning to repaint. Even buyers who nominally like the colour often feel the wall commits them to a design direction they had not chosen themselves.</p>

      <p>Paint over feature walls as part of the sale preparation. Resist the urge to replace them with a different feature wall. A home that reads consistently from room to room gives buyers a clean slate to imagine their own furnishing and colour choices. That imagination is where willingness to pay comes from.</p>

      <p>The exception is a genuinely integrated architectural feature, like a wood-panelled wall in a period home or a double-height stone fireplace. Those should be preserved as they are, not painted out. The test is whether the feature is part of the building's character or a decorator's choice overlaid on top of it.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Bedrooms, bathrooms, and kitchens</h2>
      <p>Bedrooms should follow the same neutral palette as the rest of the home. Resist the temptation to paint a child's bedroom in a bright colour for the campaign. Buyers are imagining their own children, who may not be the same age or have the same preferences. A neutral wall that can be styled with bedding and art reads as flexible and clean.</p>

      <p>Bathrooms are often painted unnecessarily. If the tile extends to the ceiling or close to it, there is usually very little wall surface to paint. Where there is wall above a half-tiled wainscot or around a vanity, the same neutral as the rest of the home is the safest choice, with a mould-resistant paint designed for wet areas.</p>

      <p>Kitchens are rarely fully repainted for a sale. The wall area in a modern kitchen is typically small, and most of the visual impact comes from the joinery, splashback, and benchtops. A fresh coat on the wall above a tile splashback, in the same colour as adjacent living spaces, is usually all that is needed. Repainting kitchen cabinetry is a separate and much larger project, with its own return-on-investment calculation.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Heritage and character considerations</h2>
      <p>Brisbane's inner east has a high proportion of pre-war Queenslanders, interwar homes, and mid-century properties with original architectural character. For those homes, the paint strategy needs to respect the architecture. A 1920s Queenslander painted inside in a stark modern white can read as mismatched, with the period ceilings, VJ walls, and timber detailing fighting the finish.</p>

      <p>The safer choice for character homes is a warmer white like Dulux Natural White or Antique White USA on walls, with original timber features preserved or lightly refreshed rather than painted over. Original picture rails, ceiling roses, and timber skirtings should generally be retained in their natural finish or in a soft off-white that matches the period. Painting every piece of heritage timber in modern semi-gloss white almost always reduces value by erasing the very character that the buyer pool is paying for.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Finishes, preparation, and quality</h2>
      <p>Low-sheen acrylic is the standard choice for walls in the Brisbane climate. It is washable, photographs without glare, and holds up to the humidity better than flat finishes. Semi-gloss for trim, doors, and architraves. Flat ceiling white for ceilings. Avoid high-gloss on anything other than a genuine period feature where it is historically appropriate.</p>

      <p>Preparation is where amateur repaints give themselves away. Filling every nail hole, sanding every skirting edge, cutting in cleanly at ceiling and cornice lines, and applying two full coats of a quality paint rather than one coat of a cheap paint is what separates a repaint that reads as fresh from one that reads as rushed. A good painter will budget two-thirds of the time for preparation and one-third for paint application. If a quote implies the opposite, the finish will show it.</p>

      <p>Engage a professional painter for any interior repaint intended to support a sale campaign. The labour cost is a small fraction of the total value lift a good paint job produces, and the finish quality gap between a trade painter and a weekend DIY effort is visible in every photograph. Get three quotes, look at photographs of past work, and confirm the painter is using the paint you have specified rather than substituting a cheaper brand.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Timing the work</h2>
      <p>Interior repaint work should be completed at least two weeks before photography. Paint needs time to cure, the smell needs to clear, and any touch-ups need to be finished before the stylist moves furniture in. Rushing the paint to finish two days before photography rarely produces a clean result and often leaves visible touch-up marks in the final images.</p>

      <p>Plan the repaint to finish four weeks before listing, style the home through weeks three and two, photograph in week two, and launch at the beginning of week one. That sequence gives paint, styling, and marketing each enough time to do their work without compressing or compromising each other.</p>

